      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "1. Instead of using a standard adjacency list or DSU, use a more space-efficient data structure like a BitSet or a Bloom filter to represent the graph. This will drastically reduce memory usage.\n2. Preprocess the edges to eliminate duplicates and self-loops, as they don't contribute to connectivity.\n3. Use a modified DFS or BFS that only processes nodes that haven't been visited yet. This way, we don't need to store all nodes in memory.\n4. Use a generator function to lazily load edges and process them one by one, avoiding loading the entire graph into memory at once.\n5. Finally, count the connected components as you process the graph.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to pass the memory limit constraint. Good luck!",
